  "prompt": "How do you determine the unit of quantity of electricity?",
  "response": "The unit of quantity of electricity is measured in coulombs (C). One coulomb is defined as the amount of electric charge transported by a current of one ampere in one second. Mathematically, it can be expressed as:\n\n1 Coulomb (C) = 1 Ampere (A) \u00d7 1 Second (s)\n\nTo determine the quantity of electricity in a given situation, you can use the formula:\n\nQ = I \u00d7 t\n\nWhere:\n- Q is the quantity of electricity (in coulombs)\n- I is the electric current (in amperes)\n- t is the time (in seconds)\n\nFor example, if a current of 2 amperes flows through a circuit for 5 seconds, the quantity of electricity can be calculated as:\n\nQ = 2 A \u00d7 5 s = 10 C\n\nSo, the quantity of electricity in this case would be 10 coulombs.",
